  "When combining equations in a Hess's law calculation, substances appearing on both sides of the combined equations cancel out, just as in algebraic simplification.": "",
  "What does 'Hess's law' mean?": "",
  "A law about conservation of mass under most circumstances involving Hess": "",
  "A law stating that all reactions are reversible when considering all relevant Hess factors": "",
  "A law governing the speed of reactions in most scenarios involving Hess factors": "",
  "A law stating that the total enthalpy change for a reaction is independent of the pathway between reactants and products": "",
  "Hess's law states that the enthalpy change of a chemical reaction depends only on the initial and final states, not on the path or number of intermediate steps taken.": "",
  "What does 'thermochemical equation' mean?": "",
  "An equation written at high temperature": "",
  "An equation that shows only the heat produced": "",
  "A balanced equation that includes the enthalpy change (Delta H) for the reaction": "",
  "Any balanced chemical equation": "",
  "A thermochemical equation is a balanced chemical equation that includes the physical states of all species and the enthalpy change (Delta H) for the reaction as written.": "",
  "What does 'enthalpy diagram' mean?": "",
  "A plot of temperature vs time": "",
  "A diagram showing relative enthalpy levels of reactants, products, and intermediates": "",
  "A phase diagram showing state changes": "",
  "A diagram of molecular bonds": "",
  "An enthalpy diagram (or energy level diagram) shows the relative enthalpy levels of reactants and products, with arrows indicating the enthalpy changes for each step.": "",
  "What does 'Born-Haber cycle' mean?": "",
  "A cycle of heating and cooling a substance": "",
  "An application of Hess's law to calculate the lattice energy of an ionic compound using a series of steps": "",
  "A cycle describing the steps of a catalytic reaction": "",
  "A method for determining reaction mechanisms": "",
  "The Born-Haber cycle uses Hess's law to calculate the lattice energy of an ionic compound by breaking the formation process into a series of steps with known enthalpy values.": "",
  "What does 'lattice energy' mean?": "",
  "The kinetic energy of ions in a solid": "",
  "The energy released when gaseous ions combine to form one mole of an ionic solid": "",
  "The energy of covalent bonds in a crystal": "",
  "The energy required to melt a crystal": "",
  "Lattice energy is the energy released when gaseous cations and anions come together to form one mole of a crystalline ionic compound. It is a measure of ionic bond strength.": "",
  "What does 'enthalpy of sublimation' mean?": "",
  "The enthalpy change when a solid converts directly to a gas": "",
  "The enthalpy change when a gas condenses to a liquid": "",
  "The enthalpy of forming a solid from atoms": "",
  "The enthalpy change when a solid melts": "",
  "The enthalpy of sublimation is the energy required to convert one mole of a solid directly to a gas without passing through the liquid phase.": "",
  "What does 'ionization energy' mean in the context of Born-Haber cycles?": "",
  "The energy to break a bond in a molecule": "",
  "The energy needed to dissolve a salt": "",
  "The energy required to remove an electron from a gaseous atom or ion": "",
  "The energy released when an ion forms a compound": "",
  "Ionization energy is the energy required to remove an electron from a gaseous atom or ion, converting it to a cation in the Born-Haber cycle.": "",
  "What does 'electron affinity' mean?": "",
  "The number of electrons in the outer shell": "",
  "The attraction between an electron and a proton": "",
  "The energy released when a neutral gaseous atom gains an electron to form an anion": "",
  "The energy needed to remove an electron": "",
